03909nmm a2200541Ia 9780801458644DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014586447 a10.7591/97808014586442doi  a(DE-B1597)481721  a(OCoLC)987936718  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a610.7322200aWhen Chicken Soup Isn't Enough :bStories of Nurses Standing Up for Themselves, Their Patients, and Their Profession /ced. by Suzanne Gordon. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Culture and Politics of Health Care Work0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe reassuring bromides of "chicken soup for the soul" provide little solace for nurses—and the people they serve—in real-life hospitals, nursing homes, schools of nursing, and other settings. In the minefield of modern health care, there are myriad obstacles to quality patient care—including work overload, inadequate funds for nursing education and research, and poor communication between and within the professions, to name only a few. The seventy RNs whose stories are collected here by the award-winning journalist Suzanne Gordon know that effective advocacy isn't easy. It takes nurses willing to stand up for themselves, their coworkers, their patients, and the public.When Chicken Soup Isn't Enough brings together compelling personal narratives from a wide range of nurses from across the globe. The assembled profiles in professional courage provide new insight into the daily challenges that RNs face in North America and abroad—and how they overcome them with skill, ingenuity, persistence, and individual and collective advocacy at work and in the community. In this collection, we meet RNs working at the bedside, providing home care, managing hospital departments, teaching and doing research, lobbying for quality patient care, and campaigning for health care reform. Their stories are funny, sad, deeply moving, inspiring, and always revealing of the different ways that nurses make their voices heard in the service of their profession. The risks and rewards, joys and sorrows, of nursing have rarely been captured in such vivid first-person accounts. Gordon and the authors of the essays contained in this book have much to say about the strengths and shortcomings of health care today—and the role that nurses play as irreplaceable agents of change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aSocial Work. 4aSociology & Social Science.1 aGordon, Suzanne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145864440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801458644423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801458644/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles